<TEXT>
more than 45000 bottles of a prescription eye 
solution are being recalled because that may be contaminated with 
bacteria that could cause a sightthreatening infection in a 
scratched eye officials said friday 
the product made by fisons corp of rochester ny is 
opticrom generically known as cromolyn sodium in a 4 percent 
ophthalmic solution it is sold in 10 milliliter bottles the food 
and drug administration said 
the two lots being recalled are kf7a and kf35v the lot 
identification appears on the bottom of the bottle and also on the 
flap of the cardboard container the bottle comes in 
the fda advises consumers to return bottles in these lots to 
their pharmacies the solution is prescribed to treat several rare 
eye conditions 
testing by fisons plc pharmaceutical division in the united 
kingdom found bacillus cereus in lot kf7a and an unidentified 
bacillus in the other lot the fda said 
both lots were distributed nationwide and in puerto rico the 
fda said that about 114 bottles of kf7a and 45223 bottles of kf35v 
were distributed 
