<TEXT>
it was the moment arjan xhaferi had been 
waiting for 
hundreds of albanians were surging into foreign embassies in the 
capital he learned one night two weeks ago in no time the 
32yearold factory worker was on the phone to his friends in 
shkodar a city in northern albania 
i said hurry we can win our liberty he recalled a few 
nights later xhaferi his pregnant wife his daughter and their 
friends clambered over the wall of the west german embassy in 
tirana 
on friday they were among more than 4000 people who were 
ferried out of albania to italy in a sealift set up through un 
mediation 
i have sacrificed everything even my life said xhaferi 
speaking in italian we have searched for liberty for so much 
time 
he gazed at his wife who was smiling despite the heat and 
fatigue a hand resting on her swollen belly 
we hope the baby is free he said grinning shyly 
the xhaferis had some particular reasons for being unhappy in 
albania 
a friend had tried unsuccessfully to flee the country and his 
family was under pressure from the government xhaferi said 
but they had more general reasons too the poor quality of life 
and the ban on the practice of religion which hurt the roman 
catholic family 
albania was 70 percent moslem before the government closed all 
mosques and churches in 1967 
we want freedom we want a new economy a new government and a 
new society of democracy xhaferi declared 
while the west german embassy provided the door to a new life 
the xhaferis did not have an easy time there 
every day the albanian government shut off the water for 
several hours in the building packed with 3200 refugees toilets 
stopped working and overflowed men slept in a few rooms crowded 
on the floor women and children in other rooms 
nonetheless he says west german diplomats were wonderful 
giving them meat and bread as well as milk for 5yearold arrisa 
the xhaferis finally got to leave the embassy late thursday 
after ferries sent by western european governments for the refugees 
docked in the port of durres 
but the ordeal was not over yet the heat in the 
governmentowned busses was oppressively high and it was 
impossible to open the windows xhaferi said 
their ferry left at 3 am friday and pulled into port seven 
hours later still ahead for the family was a 30hour train trip to 
west germany 
but there were no complaints 
we are leaving communism forever xhaferi grinned 
</TEXT>
