<TEXT>
while the government is redesigning currency 
to thwart counterfeiters it ought to make the bills more 
attractive says a man who used to run the treasurys 
moneyproducing agency 
the principles and history of a country are recounted in the 
art of bank notes robert j leuver told the senate banking 
committee on friday we seem to have lost the art majesty and 
history provided in our national bank notes of 1896 silver 
certificates of 1896 and the beautiful 2 bill of 1976 
the tin lizzy vintage car on the back of the 10 bill 
harkens to a different time and does not afford the counterfeit 
detection we need said leuver a former chief of the bureau of 
engraving and printing who now directs the american numismatic 
association 
leuver said most of the anticounterfeiting deterrents built 
into currency are less effective than they could be because of the 
50yearold design of the bills 
as an example he mentioned the mylar security thread that 
soon will become a part of every greenback the thread will include 
printing that can be read only in indirect light 
this deterrent will particularly thwart counterfeiters who ply 
their trade outside of the united states he said however the 
current design of the note obscures the thread or causes it to 
be overlooked 
leuver along with officials from the secret service and the 
bureau of engraving and printing endorsed a bill to toughen laws 
against counterfeiting 
carl v dalessandro assistant director of the bureau told the 
committee that currency and other securities can be counterfeited 
with remarkable accuracy using widely available computers printers 
and copiers 
the potential counterfeiter no longer requires any particular 
expertise in printing but only the inclination and the electronic 
devices he said 
just as the counterfeiting of currency by multicolored copiers 
has increased greatly over the past few years so will the use of 
computer laser scanners as a means to scan store and subsequently 
counterfeit currency said william j ebert who heads the secret 
services counterfeit division 
ebert said 138 million of counterfeit currency was passed in 
this country last year and 752 million was seized before it was 
put into circulation some 103 million in bogus us bills was 
confiscated abroad 
the measure dallesandro and ebert endorsed would make it a 
crime to possess any lasertype device the treasury department 
concludes would help a counterfeiter and would ensure that 
duplication of currency by any electronic method is illegal 
it would bar private possession of any counterfeitdeterrent 
device including watermarks and seals just as the distinctive 
paper on which greenbacks are printed now is protected 
but kenneth a wasch executive director of the software 
publishers association whose members develop computer programs 
said the bill is so broad that many heretofore legal activities 
may now be made illegal 
he said the prohibition on private possession of certain optical 
devices could mean document scanners desktop computers a number 
of software programs laser printers and other hightech wonders 
could be outlawed even though they are in use everywhere 
</TEXT>
