<TEXT>
president bush is eager to sign civil rights 
legislation aimed at drawing millions of disabled americans into 
the work force and marketplace 
this legislation will serve as a declaration of independence 
for millions of persons with disabilities in this country bush 
said friday after a 916 senate vote sent the americans with 
disabilities act to the white house 
it will change the way we live forever said the chief 
senate sponsor democrat tom harkin of iowa 
in a dramatic conclusion of nine months of debate on the bill 
harkin addressed the senate in sign language as a tribute to his 
brother frank who is deaf 
i wanted to say to my brother frank that today was my proudest 
day in 16 years in congress harkin explained 
the bill aims at doing for people with mental and physical 
impairments what the 1964 civil rights act strived to do for blacks 
and other minorities it bans discrimination against the disabled 
in employment public accommodations transportation and 
telecommunications 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said bush would sign the 
bill into law as soon as a ceremony could be arranged probably as 
early as next week fitzwater called the measure one of the most 
important accomplishments of this administration 
civil rights lobbyists complain that the white house did little 
to help the bill after the senate initially passed it last 
september by a 768 vote fridays vote was on a compromise version 
theres no question that president bush and attorney general 
dick thornburgh played a constructive role in fashioning a 
bipartisan consensus in the senate in 1989 said ralph g neas 
executive director of the leadership conference on civil rights an 
umbrella group for civil rights and labor organizations we have 
applauded that effort 
but neas added theres no question that since september 1989 
the administration has done very little 
in the meantime the bill went through a series of house 
hearings leading to house approval of its own version 40320 in 
may the house passed the compromise 37728 thursday night 
between the original votes in the house and senate lawmakers 
were lobbied strongly by the chamber of commerce and the national 
federation of independent business which complained the bill is 
excessively burdensome 
although a few minor concessions emerged the senate bill 
remained basically intact the senate bill had been refined after 
extensive negotiations with the white house 
the bill was conceived in 1988 by the national council on 
disability a 15member commission appointed by president reagan 
the original legislation introduced by sen lowell weicker 
rconn and cosponsored by harkin was scuttled because of various 
problems harkin sponsored the new bill last year 
the final hurdle was an amendment from the house that would have 
let employers reassign aidsinfected workers from foodhandling 
duties 
under an agreement reached early thursday by house and senate 
negotiators aidsinfected workers could be reassigned only if the 
department of health and human services found that the disease 
could be passed along through contact with food 
hhs secretary louis w sullivan and other officials say no 
evidence exists that aids is spread through food or casual contact 
in an effort to ease its impact on business lawmakers included 
language phasing in the bills requirements the bill also exempts 
from the hiring provisions businesses with fewer than 15 employees 
voting against the bill friday were sens christopher s bond 
rmo jake garn rutah jesse helms rnc gordon humphrey 
rnh steve symms ridaho and malcolm wallop rwyo 
not voting were sens jay rockefeller dwva james a 
mcclure ridaho and alan k simpson rwyo 
