<TEXT>
the agency that ran nuclear weapons production 
in the 1940s rejected secret advice to study cancer risks for its 
workers even though it knew some were exposed to large doses of 
radiation documents show 
records of the atomic energy commission also show that airborne 
emissions of radiation continued at the hanford nuclear reservation 
in washington state from the plants startup in 1944 until at 
least the mid1950s 
the aec was a predecessor to the energy department which owns 
all the governments nuclear arms factories 
the government first acknowledged the hanford problems publicly 
in 1986 although much information about radiation releases there 
is still classified as secret 
on thursday a panel of health experts disclosed that one in 20 
residents living near hanford on the columbia river near richland 
wash between late 1944 and december 1947 absorbed a level of 
radiation equal to 1200 times what the energy department now 
considers a safe limit 
the panel of independent health specialists said the releases of 
radioactive iodine a byproduct of extracting plutonium from 
uranium were serious enough to justify a study of potential 
illnesses or deaths related to the emissions 
the release of the report marked the first time the government 
has publicly acknowledged that radiation releases from its nuclear 
arms factories could have harmed human health 
yet the government was made aware shortly after the hanford 
plant began operating in september 1944 that airborne contaminants 
posed serious health risks 
in a march 1948 report the radiation health and safety chief at 
hanford wrote that emissions of radioactive particles from the 
plants plutoniumprocessing buildings can produce radiation 
damage he also said that the theoretical possibility of injury 
developing 10 to 15 years from now poses a serious problem 
the atomic energy commission rejected a recommendation by its 
biology and medicine advisory panel in early 1949 that studies be 
conducted on possible links between cancer and hanford workers 
exposure to radiation aec records show 
the aec records were cited in a december 1989 report by the 
democratic majority staff of the senate governmental affairs 
committee that recommended the energy department make public more 
of its longsecret data on radiation releases at hanford 
the latest government admission of potential health hazards to 
people near hanford is part of an evolution of openness about 
nuclear weapons operations 
in a 1945 government report that revealed the existence of the 
oncesecret hanford and other plants an army official involved in 
the project wrote factors of safety used in plant design and 
operation are so great that the hazards of the home and the family 
car are far greater for the personnel than any arising from the 
plants 
gene plock who worked as an engineer at hanfords 
plutoniumprocessing buildings from 1946 to 1950 said in an 
interview friday that he and others in his work crew were informed 
of the emissions problem in late 1946 months after it was 
discovered by general electric co which ran hanford under a 
government contract 
plock said he and some other workers then began wearing 
protective masks 
he said he recommended that military guards outside the building 
also be informed and that they be required to wear protective 
masks he said ge rejected his suggestion 
their response was no lets not alarm them he said 
the hanford study released thursday contains the most specific 
information known to the public about radiation releases at that 
facility yet it tells only part of the story of accidental and 
intentional emissions of radiation from hanford 
in addition to the radioactive iodine significant amounts of 
plutonium particles ruthenium americium and other potentially 
cancercausing products were released from processing stacks on the 
560squaremile plant in 1940s and 50s according to aec records 
</TEXT>
