propellants and biodegradable cleansing products are making their 
way onto the market 
nonremovable tabs on beverage cans replacing the throwaway 
pull tab were introduced only this year that antilitter move has 
been effect for years in the united states 
a recent fashion fad has been clothing with floral and plant 
patterns and some traditional staples of the japanese diet such 
as buckwheat noodles are being marketed as health foods to tie in 
to the ecomarketing trend 
the japan environment association a government group judges 
certain products as pollutionfree and awards an ecomark 
designation to be used in marketing them 
consumers should realize they can somehow live without harming 
the environment says kyoko kato a spokeswoman for the 
association 
but there are no scientific standards for the awarding of the 
ecomark which has been granted to 513 products companies pay a 
fee ranging from 250 to 660 when they submit products for 
approval 
ms kato says she suggested setting up other categories of the 
ecomark for products with some specific environmental benefit 
such as recyclable cans and bottles but there have been no takers 
yoko tomiyama acting director of the japan consumer union said 
she thought it might be more useful to identify products that are 
bad for the environment 
but many people just dont care she said 
many japanese companies are feeling pressured to show concern 
for the environment even if its as much a matter of style as 
substance 
