and that american policy should be based first and foremost upon 
preventing the return of the khmer rouge 
senate majority leader george mitchell dmaine and a 
bipartisan group of 10 other senators suggest in the letter that 
bush should open the door to contacts between the united states and 
the vietnamesebacked phnom penh government of hun sen 
they also ask bush to implement a congressionally authorized aid 
program for children who are victims of the countrys civil war and 
loosen restrictions on us development and humanitarian aid to 
cambodia 
the letter circulated for signatures last week is the latest 
sign of growing congressional opposition to a decadeold policy 
which sends us aid to a loose political coalition fighting the 
hun sen government 
it has become increasingly clear that the khmer rouge whose 
regime was responsible for the deaths of more than a million 
cambodians in the 1970s could be indirectly riding the us 
support back into power as the dominant member of the coalition 
while the bush administration insists that none of the us aid 
