<TEXT>
the winds of democracy blowing from 
eastern europe have reached kenya setting off bloody street 
battles in what had been considered the most stable nation of black 
africa 
several political explosions have rocked africa south of the 
sahara this year demands for reform have shaken other oneparty 
governments in ivory coast gabon zambia cameroon zaire and 
benin 
analysts say the protests reflect awareness that oneparty rule 
was swept aside in eastern europe last year and the weariness of 
africans with often authoritarian and corrupt leadership 
in kenya at least 28 people were killed in riots that began at 
a banned rally for multiparty politics july 7 the demonstrators 
stoned a plainclothes policeman and officers responded with tear 
gas and gunfire starting four days of street battles that spread 
to other parts of the country 
multiparty democracy is an international catchword which has 
been adopted by all those who have a grievance against the 
government said a western diplomat based in nairobi 
they may not know what it means but they know that they are 
unhappy and that what theyve got hasnt worked said the 
diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity 
rising food prices skyrocketing debt burgeoning populations 
and steady economic decline have added fuel to the political fires 
in zambia a failed coup july 1 followed five days of the worst 
urban violence in the nations history at least 23 people were 
killed in student riots over food price increases 
the students also demanded westernstyle democracy and the 
ouster of president kenneth kaunda who leads the united national 
independence party since 1972 the only legal political movement in 
the southern african country 
protests against austerity measures and corruption in ivory 
coast in march grew into violent antigovernment demonstrations 
demanding that president felix houphouetboigny relinquish his 
30year monopoly on power 
the protests forced him to legalize political organizations 
other than his own democratic party 
president omar bongo of gabon installed a multiparty system in 
may after a coup attempt late last year and student protests in 
january and february france sent troops to protect oil workers 
when more riots broke out in may 
benin also adopted political pluralism after dropping a 
marxistleninist style of government late last year 
paul biya cameroons president came to power in 1983 promising 
more democracy but his government has cracked down on advocates of 
pluralism since february 
six people were killed at a prodemocracy rally and authorities 
arrested 10 prominent citizens who tried to form an alternative 
party to his democratic rally of the cameroonian people 
kenyas president daniel arap moi appears to be following the 
cameroonian model 
his government has arrested and charged more than 1400 people 
in connection with the riots and threatens continued use of force 
against prodemocracy demonstrators seventeen people have been 
detained without charge including the most prominent advocates of 
multiparty politics 
moi who has governed kenya since 1978 contends political 
