<TEXT>
mikhail s gorbachev on saturday cleared the 
communist party politburo of the countrys most important officials 
in a final break with a decadesold precept of total party 
domination 
a new central committee elected on the last day of the partys 
28th congress in turn chose a 24member politburo packed with the 
communist party leaders of the 15 republics moderate reformers and 
political unknowns 
gorbachev and his newly elected deputy vladimir ivashko were 
the only holdovers from the previous 12man politburo 
it was clear the politburo would not wield the total power it 
once had but government ministers remain in place and they appear 
now to be the most powerful men in the soviet union 
gorbachev holds government power as soviet president while he 
continues to lead the party even though they are no longer 
politburo members prime minister nikolai i ryzhkov remains in 
charge of the economy dmitri t yazov remains defense minister 
vladimir a kryuchkov is still kgb chief and eduard a shevardnadze 
remains foreign minister 
the structural changes move their base of power from the 
communist party apparatus to the government a goal that gorbachev 
has espoused for at least two years he has tried to reshape the 
party so it concerns itself with broad policy goals rather than the 
countrys daytoday affairs 
before gorbachevs reforms began any high government position 
was secondary to the officials standing in the communist party 
until saturday it was understood that combination with a high 
party position was an indication of a government officials power 
the new composition of the politburo underscores that the 
party fully breaks with the former practice when it was organically 
built into the command and administrative system and was on the 
top of the hierarchy said ivan frolov the editor of the party 
newspaper pravda and a new politburo member 
it will now be a force competing with other social and 
political forces and asserting its advantages mostly in the 
ideological and political struggle he told a news conference 
ryzhkov kryuchkov and yazov remain members of the 412member 
central committee shevardnadze however does not 
shevardnadze and gorbachev adviser alexander n yakovlev a 
member of gorbachevs presidential council said during the 
congress that they did not see the need to remain on the politburo 
gorbachevs traditionalist rival yegor k ligachev was trounced 
by ivashko in his bid for the partys no 2 job and announced he 
was going home to siberia to write a book 
the leader of the radical reform wing boris n yeltsin quit 
the party on the day before the congress ended and some of the 
countrys most prominent reformers quickly joined him 
gorbachev expressed contempt for those who quit the party 
but acknowledged that the communists were facing the beginning of a 
multiparty system he pledged that the party would try to help 
government bodies rather than simply dominate them 
frolov said that in addition to the heads of party organizations 
in the soviet republics himself gorbachev and ivashko the new 
politburo will include 
alexander s dzasokhov a former ambassador to syria and 
currently chairman of the supreme soviet parliaments international 
affairs commission he will be responsible for party ideology 
yuri prokofiev the moscow communist party chief a job that in 
the past has entitled the holder to politburo status prokofiev is 
known as a moderate reformer 
galina semyonova editorinchief of peasant woman 
magazine she will be responsible for womens issues 
gennady yanayev who became head of the central council of 
trade unions this year after labor unrest began spreading through 
the country he will be responsible for international affairs 
oleg shenin the party leader in the vast krasnoyarsk region of 
siberia his will handle organizational issues 
igor stroyev elevated last year to the partys secretariat by 
gorbachev he will be responsible for farm issues 
boris gidaspov the leningrad party chief whom reformers suspect 
of being a hardliner trying to undermine gorbachev was elected a 
national party secretary 
it is unclear how the politburos function will change but it 
appeared unlikely to meet as frequently weekly politburo meetings 
for years thrashed out decisions on all key policy questions 
by putting the party chiefs of the 15 republics on the 
politburo gorbachev has tried to give the party a better forum for 
discussing ethnic issues they range from hardliners such as 
mikolas burokjavicus the head of the small lithuanian party loyal 
to moscow to georgian givi gumbaridze who is leading his 
republics party to endorse the drive for local sovereignty 
their selection ensures that the partys highest body no longer 
will be dominated by russians who gradually worked their way 
through the party apparatus to important jobs in moscow 
frolov reported a very heated debate in the central 
committee over which of two candidates from the baltic republic of 
estonia to select they settled on ennarno sillari a 
representative of the faction that has announced its intention to 
split from the party 
 
