<TEXT>
abortion activists in at least three states are taking their 
fight directly to the people with initiative petition drives 
designed to steer around the opposition of elected officials 
the initiative campaigns reflect a nationwide trend toward 
direct voter involvement in hotly disputed issues and a 
frustration on the part of abortion activists with the pace of 
change 
antiabortion forces appear to have gathered enough signatures 
for two ballot initiatives in oregon and for a legislative 
initiative in michigan that gives legislators another chance to 
pass abortion restrictions that had been vetoed by the governor 
in nevada prochoice forces have succeeded in getting an 
abortion rights measure on the november ballot 
other abortionrelated initiative drives were mounted this year 
in oklahoma colorado missouri and washington but all but 
washingtons appear to be dead or dying 
prochoice forces are still collecting signatures in washington 
for an initiative designed to ensure that abortion remains legal 
even if the us supreme court overturns roe vs wade the ruling 
that legalized abortion 
abortionrelated initiatives have become an increasingly popular 
tactic in the 17 years since roe vs wade there have been 11 such 
initiatives since 1973 including four in 1986 and three in 1988 
its accelerating said patrick b mcguigan who studies 
voter initiatives for the free congress research and education 
foundation in washington thats hardly surprising he added given 
the volatility of the issue and the general growth of initiatives 
as a political tool 
antiabortion forces lost all four battles in 1986 and won all 
three in 1988 this year mcguigan said i think you can expect 
mixed results 
both sides in the abortion battle say they would prefer to gain 
their victories in the legislatures but in some cases they say 
the initiative is the best tool 
our basic perspective said burke balch of the national 
right to life committee is that in general we resort to 
initiatives and referenda only as a last resort 
that reasoning prompted antiabortion forces in oregon where 
the legislature leans strongly toward abortion rights to mount 
petition drives to place two initiatives on the november ballot 
one would outlaw abortion except in cases of rape or incest or 
to save a womans life the other requires a parent to be notified 
of a minors abortion 48 hours in advance 
backers of the initiatives already have filed what they believe 
are enough signatures to qualify for the ballot state officials 
are in the process of checking the signatures to verify them 
in michigan antiabortion activists seized on the initiative as 
a way of foiling gov james blanchard who vetoed a parental 
consent bill earlier this year 
right to life of michigan has filed petitions bearing 333187 
signatures about 140000 more than are required 
if enough signatures are valid the parental consent issue would 
go back to the legislature this fall if it passes blanchard would 
not be allowed to veto it if it loses the issue will be put 
before voters probably in november 1992 
in washington where the initiative system is similar 
signatures are due by jan 3 
the nevada initiative which has already qualified for the 
ballot would bar state legislators from changing the states 
existing abortion law 
in colorado an antiabortion initiative campaign was set back 
earlier this month when the state supreme court found that it was 
not clearly drafted and ordered it rewritten 
effectively this blows us out of the water said william l 
woodley president of the coalition for your right to know which 
sponsored the parental consent measure 
in missouri an abortion rights group said last week that it 
would fall short of the number of signatures needed to place a 
constitutional amendment on the ballot the measure would have 
repealed the restrictive abortion law that the us supreme court 
upheld last year in its webster vs reproductive health services 
ruling 
in oklahoma a group of baptist ministers is backing a petition 
drive that would allow voters to decide whether to outlaw abortions 
except in cases of rape incest or fetal deformity or when the 
mother is at risk 
however even if the sponsors collect enough signatures 
abortion rights activists have already said they would file suit 
against the measure and it appears likely to be delayed beyond the 
november election 
